{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9edd1e74-6641-4242-b38c-f33657c6ddcc","content":"Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your scenario directly:\n\n### 1. `nvarchar(max)` → native `json` column type (Azure SQL)\n\nWith `UseAzureSql()`, EF Core 10 defaults to the native `json` column type for primitive collections (`string[] Tags`) and owned types mapped via `ToJson()`. Running `migrations add` will emit `AlterColumn` operations changing `nvarchar(max)` → `json`.\n\n**Mitigation** — explicitly pin the column type if you want to avoid the schema change:\n\n```csharp\nentity.Property(e => e.Tags).HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\");\n```\n\nOr accept the migration and let columns move to native `json`.\n\n---\n\n### 2. OPENJSON translation change for `.Contains()`\n\nEF Core 10 changes the SQL generated for `.Contains()` on in-memory/parameterized collections (e.g. `List<int>`). The OPENJSON call now uses a **typed `WITH` clause**:\n\n```sql\n-- EF Core 9 (untyped)\nWHERE x IN (SELECT [value] FROM OPENJSON(@p))\n\n-- EF Core 10 (typed)\nWHERE x IN (SELECT [value] FROM OPENJSON(@p) WITH ([value] int '$'))\n```\n\nThis eliminates implicit `nvarchar→int` conversions (better index usage) but **changes query plans**. Existing plan-guide or performance baselines may break.\n\n**Mitigation** — benchmark affected queries after upgrading; the new plans are generally better but verify with your data/indexes.\n\n---\n\n### 3. `--framework` now **required** for multi-target projects\n\nEF Core 10 design-time tools no longer silently pick a TFM when the project multi-targets. Running:\n\n```bash\ndotnet ef migrations add MyMigration        # ❌ fails\ndotnet ef migrations add MyMigration --framework net10.0  # ✅\n```\n\n**Mitigation** — update CI scripts and developer docs to always pass `--framework`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"68ae2c04-b78c-471c-90eb-15ff8321cf7a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about EF Core 10 breaking changes that a